entries.meaning: An utterance of oh; a spoken expression of surprise, acknowledgement, etc.
examples: There were ohs and ahs, and the people twisted about as they looked for her. Then they began to applaud.

verbs.description: oh (third-person singular simple present ohs, present participle ohing, simple past and past participle ohed)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To utter the interjection oh; to express surprise, etc.
examples: A quarter of an hour elapsed, and then, after several rings at the door-bell, a smothered laugh, and a good deal of ohing and ahing, the door was thrown open, and one by one, as they were announced, in came the expected characters.

description: From Middle English o, oo, from Old English ō, from Latin ō.

entries.meaning: the letter O, o (more commonly spelled o)
examples: One genuine recycled local glass of aitch-two-oh

entries.meaning: the digit 0 (especially in representations of speech)
